            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-04-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-04-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="68"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d68">
                <head>68. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>) and the Director of the
                    Office of Management and Budget (<persName corresp="#p_MJT_1"
                        >McIntyre</persName>) to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d68fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>
                        Material, Country File, Box 58, Oman: 4–9/80. Secret. Sent for information.
                            <persName corresp="#p_ADL_1">Aaron</persName> initialed for <persName
                            corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName> and sent the memorandum to
                            <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> under an April 1
                        memorandum that recommended <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                        approve the approach outlined in the memorandum, noting that “<persName
                            corresp="#p_MJT_1">Jim McIntyre</persName> supports this package.” An
                        unknown hand circled that sentence and noted <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                            >Carter</persName>’s approval. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                            >Carter</persName> initialed the memorandum. The memorandum was in
                        response to a March 31 handwritten note in which <persName
                            corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> noted: “I understood Sat. that Oman
                        package would be ≈$20 mil in ’82 and ’83. Get with Jim &amp; give me a
                        complete picture of what is proposed.” (Ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-04-01">April 1, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Aid to Oman (U)</item>
                </list>
                <p>The maximum package of economic aid to Oman proposed by the <gloss
                        target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss> was $105 million over the three fiscal years
                    1981–83 (composed of $15 million <gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> grants to
                    fund the proposed Joint Commission, $40 million <gloss target="#t_ESF_1"
                        >ESF</gloss> concessional loans, and $50 million <gloss target="#t_EXIM_1"
                        >EXIM</gloss> credits).<note n="2" xml:id="d68fn2">See <ref target="#d66"
                            >Document 66</ref>.</note> In the impending negotiations, Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BR_1">Bartholomew</persName> is instructed to offer initially
                    only the $5 million <gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> annually to support the
                    Commission. This economic aid would be in addition to <gloss target="#t_FMS_1"
                        >FMS</gloss> credits you approved earlier ($50 million over 1980–81) and
                        <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> military construction benefiting Oman
                    internally (over $100 million in 1981, probably more in later years). (S)</p>
                <p>Since Saturday,<note n="3" xml:id="d68fn3">March 29. See <ref target="#d67"
                            >Document 67</ref>.</note> we have been exploring ways to reduce the
                        <gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> component, because it will be difficult
                    to absorb within current budget planning levels and is more likely than <gloss
                        target="#t_EXIM_1">EXIM</gloss> credits to provoke criticism in Congress.
                    Although EximBank’s budget will be tight also, <persName corresp="#p_MF_1">John
                        Moore</persName>
                    <note n="4" xml:id="d68fn4">Chairman of the Export-Import Bank.</note> has told
                    us the Bank could provide all of the maximum package in the two years 1982 and
                    1983, except for the $5 million to be provided annually for the Joint
                    Commission. Accordingly, it should be feasible to limit the <gloss
                        target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> component to $5 million grant aid in each of
                    FY81, 82, and 83 ($15 million total), plus $10 million in <gloss
                        target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> loans in each of FY82 and 83 ($20 million
                    total). (S)</p>
                <p>It may be possible to avoid any increase in the <gloss target="#t_ESF_1"
                        >ESF</gloss> component beyond our minimum offer ($5 million a year for the
                    Commission): If the initial offer is not sufficient to conclude the negotiations
                    successfully, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BR_1">Bartholomew</persName> should (and
                    now plans to) seek agreement on <pb facs="0279" n="236" xml:id="pg_236"/>
                    amounts less than envisaged in our full package before offering that package.
                    This will be reinforced in a cable that we will send instructing him to limit
                    our <gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> offer to a total of $15 million per
                    year or, in a more positive tone, to indicate that <gloss target="#t_EXIM_1"
                        >EXIM</gloss> credits would make up at least 70% of our maximum
                        package.<note n="5" xml:id="d68fn5">Reference is likely to telegram 89463 to
                        Muscat, April 5. (National Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        D800169–1032)</note> (S)</p>
                <p>The complete package of offers, including the $50 million in <gloss
                        target="#t_FMS_1">FMS</gloss> credits you approved earlier for 1980–81,
                    would be as follows:</p>
                <table cols="5">
                    <row>
